Finally got to the gym this late AM. Up and down day with the snatch, as you'll see. Couple things I'd like to say here. One, I realized on the 187 barbell I wasn't punching out on the turnover like I know I can, so I made a more determined effort to do that the rest of the way. The second thing is my right knee. I clipped a manual slow motion video of it from the high pull to the catch; it drops 2-3" relative to my left knee (which, I think, is fairly well-positioned). Do you have any sense how to isolate this habit (due to mobility limitations or, perhaps, just endless repetitions and muscle memory) so we can work to correct it? It has to be playing a significant role in catching the bar forward, losing stability, etc., at those higher weights. 

Anyway, the ARs were really poorly calibrated here; I was probably losing 2 kph due to it. So, to keep to the time domain and the desired stimulus, I did 1200M each round. 11:17 / 195,Last 3 rounds: ~ 450-500 watts - ~1:52 ski - ~1:42 row / 295 complex / 325 back squat / 2:43 metcon,"185-205-220-235 / 5:51 - 5:48 - 5:42 1st round stayed on the left shoulder, 2'd round alternated (had it's benefits but not used to it), and 3rd round pushed a little harder on the bag (left shoulder only, then hit a wall at lap 8 and had to finish on right shoulder and slow way down) / will do the C2B tomorrow.",,"Did this Sunday, early afternoon:
2:15-2:12-2:12-2:14-2:13-2:12 (1:52.5/500M Pace thru, ~ 30-ft. HSW) / 175-185-195-205","Here might be a better place for me to express my thoughts on the competition. I have several things to report:

1. I was surprised at the level of nerves I experienced on the first workout (lifting complex), given the low-ish stakes of the event. I missed my first S2O, then had to triage the rest of the 6-minute lifting window to do damage control. Also, looking at the videos of all the lifts, my back leg revertied to old form, straight as an arrow. So we'll have to continue to drill the jerk position we began lasat week a lot more before it is second nature on heavy lifts under duress.

2. The last workout yielded some good things, as it was the only place I was really challenged with potential failure. The workout was a progression through oly lifts and rig movements, 20 reps apiece, starting lighter and progressing to heavier weights. I had my partner do most of the work for the buy-in rounds, since I knew I would bear the burden of the heavier snatches later on. By about the 5-minute mark, we had completed the first 4 movements, and progressed to 20 snatches @ 185. I did a set of 4, relatively quick singles (all power snatches that I hit with decent confidence), and then gave him a crack to do what he could. He failed, so I went back and did another 4. This continued throughout so that, by the end, I did all 20, in sets of 4, and while my cadence slowed some as we progressed, I didn't fail any reps, and we had enough time left over in the 12-minute cap to get the 20 BMU in (I did 14 of those as he was relegated to 2s--this workout was a little advanced for him). So, in any case, it was a good opportunity to grind through a high volume of heavy power snatches, and still be able to pivot to some high-skill gymnastics without too much dealy or difficulty.
Overall, then, I had a lot of fun, got some good work in, and got to refresh some of the feelings associated with live competition that I know will return in Birmingham.",,
